t their busi\nness on the right principle arc not a pi\nto be hurt by the fear of nossibUi\nlegislation. Times are growing bet\nter every day. What this country\nneeds Is morn optimists. I hail from\na country that believes in the booster\nand this country in every nook and\ncorner Is worth boosting, flood times\nare hero and as I believe, are here to\nNKW YOFK, Jan. 20. \"Our coun\ntry leads the world in industry,\" de\nclared Andrew Carnegie Monday, just\nbefore presiding over a meeting of the\nPeace society, \"and the records of\nour exports easily prove this.\"\nlie added: \"Any man who has not\nfaith in our republic ought to go out\nof Lu.-iness anyway.\"\nHe said that although he was not\nengaged in business now he thought\nthe outlook for the \"year was very\nbrU-ht and did not think that the\ntariff would hamper Lusintss but the\ninborn application find genius of\nAmerican business men would sur\nmount all obstacles.\n\"Thcrj are always tendencies to\nward the two extremes of pessimism\nand optimism.\" he said. \"The pess-\nimist sh-d gloom upon projects while\nthe optimist tries to tly too high but\nIt is the mean between these two\nTwo Men Are Reinstated and\nEverything is in Working\nOrder Once More on the\nDelaware and Hudson Road.\nthere is every reason to believe that\nthey will be amicably .adjusted.\nBy midr.Uht everything was run\nning smoothly, an official of the com\npany said. The first train out of Al\nbany tonight was the for tho\nnorth.\nRULES ARE MADE TO\nENSURE SAFETY AT SEA\nBoat\nfiolns More Than l.\" Miles\nI'lorn shore M\"'t Carry\nWirclos \"Apparatus.\nwhere prosperity lies and the\nican business man invariably\nthat mean.\"\nA mer\nlin tJs\nRAILROADS MAY WIN\nHIGHER RATE FIGHT\nAdministration Said to 1k in Favor\nof ranting Demand\nEastern Lines.\non\nBROTHERHOOD IN MEETING\nProf. Bishop Johnson of the high\n'school gave three readings from la\niduiih selections to the brotherhood of\nSt. Paul's M. K. church Monday\nnight which was attended by a large\naudience, other entertaining numbers\nwere presented and arrangements\nmade for a social session after the\nservice Sunday evening Feb. 1. Buffet\nluncheon was enjoyed. J\nWASHINGTON. Jan. 20. That the\nnext step toward restoring business\nconditions in the United States will be\nadministration approval of the five\nper cent increase in freight rates on\neastern railroads, was predicted Mon\nday by c.Mlclals close to the white\nhouse.\n.Pres. Wilson is loath to voice an\nopinion on the matter because it is\nbefore the interstate commerce com\nmission. Reports of business stagna\ntion among common carriers, how\never, led him to deprecate their lack\nof resiliency and to state that he had\nsome very strong opinions 011 the sub\nject. Jt is not expected that any open\ndeclaration In favor of such a move\nwill be made. The whole matter will\nbe left entirely with the commission,\nwhich will pass on the railroads' ap\nplication in its judicial capacity. Put\nit is understood that a decision favor\naide to the roads will meet with\nhearty commendation from the president.\nALBANY, N. Y.t Jan. L'O. ven\nhours after the arrival in Albany of\nGeorge. W. W. Hanger of the federal\nboard of mediation and conciliation\nthe strike of the Delaware Hudson\nrailroad employes was s-ettled and two\nhours from the time the agreement!\nwas signed nearly all of the men were\nLark at work.\nThe company reinstated the two\nmen. F. A. Siade. an engineer, and\nJames Lynch, a conductor, who were\ndismissed from the company's employ\nami on whose account the strike was\ncalled Sunday night.\nM. C Carey, International vice pres\nident, Order of Railway Cor doctors,\ngives all credit for the settlement of\nthe trouble to Mr, Hanger.\nAlthouch the two men are rein\nstated and will get their old positions\nback, yet some of the minor differ\nences that cropped out during the con\nferences held for the past ten Jays\nwere not concluded. These will go to\narbitration Tuesday morning, but\nPACKING BUSINESS PAYS\nMorris V- Co. of Chiet-go Announce a\nBi Dividend.\nLONDON. Jan. 20. The Interna\ntional Conference un Safety of Life at\nSea concluded its labors Monday.\nThe most important pleasures\nadopted were those providing that all\nships going more than 150 miles from\nshore and carrying T0 passengers shall\nbe equipped with wireless, and that\nevery passenger vessel shall be built\nwith longitudinal ami transverse wa\ntertight1 bulkheads.\nOther measures provide for the in\nstallation of proper life saving equip\nment, drills of the crews, government\ninspection of all vessels before sailing.\ntests of seaworthiness, patrol of dan-\ngemus waters and g\"r. ral warnings of j\nthe location and movements 01 ice\nbergs. S n. James Hamilton Lewis man\naged to bring about the defeat of the\nclause providing for the general arbi\ntration of treaty violations, arguing\nthat this would deprive Fnited States\ncourts of jurisdiction to adjudicate the\nrights of Fnited States citizens aboard\nships in Fnited States ports. The\ntreaty goes into effect in July, 1913.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 20. Morris\nCo., meat packers, earned 62 !-100 per\ncent on their capital stock during the\nliscal year ended Nov. 1, compared\nwith 60 4-10 per cent the previous 12\nmonths.\nTotal income Increased J23S.01U and\nnet Income $104,34 4. After allowing\ntor dividends that were double those\nfor the previous year there was a sur\nplus of 51.556,97, a decrease of $75.-\nTRY NEWS-TIMES WANT ADS\nli; jlc s& w v\nC \"v S\nINDIANA BRIEFS.\n?Z z i i i $z ye $z\n(;K1:I:.M'1I:LD. CordU .Martin.\nconvicted of robbing the bank at New\nPalestine, will spend ten to 20 years\nIn the Indiana state prison unless pa\nrob d. This will be Martin's second\ntrip to Michigan City, he having bee n\nconvicted of the same charge in the\nMarlon circuit court and the Judg\nment reversed on the ground that the\ncourt had no jurisdiction in the case,\nthe crime having been committed in\nHancock county.\nMAI1I